      <scopecontent id="aspace_85c5bf96577b7176bda6bd1df43eac66">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Walter Edwin Peck Papers are completely unprocessed. They consist of manuscripts, typescripts, and galley proofs of writings by Peck about Percy Bysshe Shelley, notes and notebooks about Shelley compiled by Peck while at Oxford, and assorted printed matter about Shelley. These materials for the most part were used by Peck for<emph render="italic">Shelley, His Life and Work</emph>(1927) and<emph render="italic">The Complete Works of Percy Bysshe Shelley</emph>(1926; co-editor Roger Ingpen). There is also a typescript of Peck's 1922 Oxford Ph.D. thesis on Shelley, and notes and assorted papers on various other romantic poets. Also among the papers is a smaller amount of memorabilia and newspaper clippings pertaining to Peck's activities while at Ashtabula (Ohio) High School, Wooster College and Hamilton College. Included here are several scrap-books, a college yearbook, postcards and photgraphs from Italy and a small amount of correspondence. Two of the scrapbooks are account books from the 1830s and 1840s into which Peck pasted memorabilia.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_6c57a303f3c04adbd283ba536a060385">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Author; M.A., Columbia, 1918; Ph.D., Oxford, 1922; 1924-1926, taught at Wesleyan University; 1926-1927, head of the English Department of Washington State College; 1927-1929 taught at Hunter College.</p>  
      </bioghist>
